  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is an 18th-century physics demonstration apparatus for teaching pulley mechanics, made by the Amsterdam instrument makers **J. Kampman and J.C. Pelletier**. It consists of a mahogany stand with two brass pulleys, used to demonstrate mechanical advantage — the principle that a small force applied over a greater distance can move a larger weight. Such apparatus was standard equipment in 18th-century physics cabinets (*fysische kabinetten*) and derives from designs published by **Willem Jacob 's Gravesande** in his influential textbook *Physices Elementa Mathematica* (1720). The instrument belongs to Teylers' **Fysisch Kabinet**, one of the oldest institutional physics collections in the Netherlands, assembled from the 1780s onward by director **Martinus van Marum**.",
